You said:
list of potential IT issues a worker may face that needs troubleshooting
ChatGPT said:

Sure! Here’s a list of common IT issues that a worker might face and typically need troubleshooting:

Hardware Issues

  • Computer won’t turn on

  • Peripheral devices not working (printer, keyboard, mouse, scanner)

  • Monitor/display issues (no signal, flickering, resolution problems)

  • Battery not charging or draining quickly (laptops)

  • Overheating devices

  • Slow computer performance due to hardware problems (e.g., failing hard drive)

Software Issues

  • Operating system crashes or freezes

  • Software won’t install or update

  • Application crashes or fails to open

  • Compatibility issues between software versions

  • Software licensing or activation problems

  • Error messages during program execution

Network and Connectivity Issues

  • No internet connection or intermittent connectivity

  • Slow internet speeds

  • Unable to connect to VPN or remote desktop

  • Network printer or shared drive not accessible

  • Wi-Fi signal problems or authentication failures

  • DNS resolution errors

Account and Access Issues

  • Forgotten passwords or account lockouts

  • Permissions denied when accessing files or systems

  • Email login issues or sync failures

  • Multi-factor authentication (MFA) problems

  • User profile corruption

Security Issues

  • Malware or virus infections

  • Phishing or suspicious email alerts

  • Firewall blocking legitimate traffic

  • Unauthorized access alerts

  • Software vulnerabilities or patches not applied

Data and Storage Issues

  • Data loss or file corruption

  • Backup failures or restoration issues

  • Insufficient disk space warnings

  • Cloud storage syncing errors

Peripheral and Mobile Device Issues

  • Mobile device not syncing with corporate systems

  • Bluetooth device pairing failures

  • Printing errors (stuck print jobs, wrong output)

  • USB device recognition problems

Performance and Configuration Issues

  • Slow boot times

  • Application or system settings misconfigured

  • Printer queue stuck or printer offline

  • Incorrect system time or time zone settings

If you want, I can also group these by categories or suggest troubleshooting steps for any of these!

how do i create and link these into my azure logic app?
ChatGPT said:

Great question! Here’s a straightforward way to create, host, and link your HTML troubleshooting pages into your Azure Logic App emails:

Step 1: Host your HTML pages somewhere accessible

Azure Logic Apps sends emails with links, so your HTML pages must be publicly (or at least internally) accessible via URLs.

Options for hosting:

  1. Azure Blob Storage (Static Website Hosting)

    • Upload your HTML files to an Azure Storage Account with Static Website hosting enabled.

    • This gives you URLs like https://<storageaccount>.z6.web.core.windows.net/password-issues.html.

  2. Azure Static Web Apps

    • Create a Static Web App to host your pages if you want a more structured or larger site.

  3. Any web server or intranet site your company uses.

Step 2: Upload your HTML files

If you choose Azure Blob Storage:

  • Create a storage account in Azure Portal.

  • Go to the storage account > Static website (under Settings) > Enable it.

  • Upload your HTML pages to the $web container (this container holds your static files).

  • Copy the URLs provided for your pages.

Step 3: Add the links to your Logic App email

In your Azure Logic App workflow:

  1. Find the step where your Logic App sends the email (usually "Send an email (V2)" or similar).

  2. In the email body (which supports HTML), insert the link to the corresponding troubleshooting page.

Example of email body snippet with a link:

html
<p>We noticed you reported a password issue. Please <a href="https://yourstorageaccount.z6.web.core.windows.net/password-issues.html" target="_blank">click here</a> to view troubleshooting steps and reset your password.</p>

Step 4 (Optional): Dynamic linking based on form input

  • Use Logic App conditions or switch cases based on the Microsoft Form response field to pick the right link.

  • For example, if the form issue type is "Password Issue", insert the password issues URL; if "VPN Issue", insert the VPN page URL, etc.

Summary:

StepWhat to do
1. Host HTML pagesUse Azure Blob Storage static website or other hosting
2. Upload HTML filesUpload to $web container (if Azure Storage)
3. Copy URLsGet the URL of each HTML page
4. Add links in Logic AppAdd URLs to email body, conditionally if needed

You said:
could we do azure blob storage
ChatGPT said:

Absolutely! Hosting your HTML pages on Azure Blob Storage with Static Website Hosting enabled is a solid choice for your university project — it’s straightforward, cloud-based, and demonstrates solid Azure skills.

Here’s a step-by-step guide to get you going:

How to Host HTML Pages on Azure Blob Storage (Static Website)

Step 1: Create an Azure Storage Account

  1. Go to the Azure Portal.

  2. Click Create a resource > Storage > Storage account.

  3. Fill in details: subscription, resource group, storage account name (must be unique), region, performance, etc.

  4. Choose Standard for Performance and StorageV2 (general purpose v2) for Account kind.

  5. Review and create the storage account.

Step 2: Enable Static Website Hosting

  1. After your storage account is deployed, open it in the portal.

  2. In the left menu, scroll to Static website under the “Data management” section.

  3. Click Enable.

  4. For Index document name, enter index.html (or your main file name).

  5. For Error document path, enter 404.html or leave blank.

  6. Click Save.

After enabling, you will get a Primary endpoint URL — this is the base URL for your static website.

Step 3: Upload Your HTML Files

  1. In your storage account, go to Containers.

  2. Open the special container called $web (this container stores your website files).

  3. Click Upload, select your HTML files (e.g., password-issues.html, vpn-issues.html, etc.).

  4. Upload.

Step 4: Access Your Pages

  • Your files will be accessible via URLs like:
    https://<your-storage-account-name>.z6.web.core.windows.net/password-issues.html

Step 5: Link These URLs in Your Azure Logic App

  • In your Logic App email action, add a link to the relevant page using the URL above.
    Example email snippet:

html
<p>If you reported a password problem, please <a href="https://yourstorageaccount.z6.web.core.windows.net/password-issues.html" target="_blank">click here</a> to troubleshoot.</p>

Optional: Automate Different Pages Based on Form Input

Use Logic App conditions or switch control to insert the correct URL based on the issue selected in the Microsoft Form.

That’s it! Your static HTML troubleshooting pages are live and integrated with your Logic App.

If you want, I can help you with commands/scripts to upload files via Azure CLI or PowerShell, or help you build conditional Logic App email content. Just ask!
